Larraine Segil (born 1948) is a South African-born entrepreneur, attorney, advisor, lecturer, author, board member and urban farmer.[1][2] She is CEO of The Little Farm Company, a Los-Angeles based family holding company which was mentioned in Forbes magazine.[3][4] Segil has been a commentator for CNN and CNBC and has been featured in Fast Company magazine and Bloomberg Business.[1][5][6]
Segil is past chair of the C200 Foundation, and past vice chair of the C200 Governing Board, a global nonprofit group of women executives, and a member of the APCO Worldwide International Advisory Council (IAC).[7][8] She is also a member of the Board of Frontier Communications and formerly of the advisory board of Edgecast, a content delivery network (CDN) company which sold to Verizon in 2013.[5] In 2009, Segil was appointed to the board of the World Health Organization (WHO) Tropical Diseases Group (TDR), in Geneva, Switzerland.[3]



